.TH "FLASHROM" "8" "Feb 27, 2026" "" "flashrom"
.SH NAME
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP \- detect, read, write, verify and erase flash chips
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
\fBflashrom\fP [\-h|\-R|\-L|
.in +2
.in +2
\-p <programmername>[:<parameters>] [\-c <chipname>]
.in +2
(\-\-flash\-name|\-\-flash\-size|
.in +2
[\-E|\-x|\-r [<file>]|\-w [<file>]|\-v [<file>]]
[(\-l <file>|\-\-ifd|\-\-fmap|\-\-fmap\-file <file>|\-\-fmap\-verify)
.in +2
[\-i <include>[:<file>]]]
.in -2
[\-\-wp\-status] [\-\-wp\-list] [\-\-wp\-enable|\-\-wp\-disable]
[\-\-wp\-range <start>,<length>|\-\-wp\-region <region>]
[\-n] [\-N] [\-f]
[\-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile>] [\-\-key\-data <value>]
[\-\-counter\-address <address>]
[\-\-get\-rpmc\-status] [\-\-write\-root\-key] [\-\-update\-hmac\-key]
[\-\-increment\-counter <current>] [\-\-get\-counter])]
.in -2
.in -2
.in -2
[\-V[V[V]]] [\-o <logfile>] [\-\-progress] [\-\-sacrifice\-ratio <ratio>]
.in -2
.fi
.sp
.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP is a utility for detecting, reading, writing, verifying and erasing flash chips.
It\(aqs often used to flash BIOS/EFI/coreboot/firmware images in\-system using a supported mainboard.
However, it also supports various external PCI/USB/parallel\-port/serial\-port based devices which can program flash
chips, including some network cards (NICs), SATA/IDE controller cards, graphics cards, the Bus Pirate device,
various FTDI FT2232/FT4232H/FT4233H/FT232H based USB devices, and more.
.sp
It supports a wide range of DIP32, PLCC32, DIP8, SO8/SOIC8, TSOP32, TSOP40, TSOP48, and BGA chips,
which use various protocols such as LPC, FWH, parallel flash, or SPI.
.SH OPTIONS
.sp
You can specify one of \fB\-h\fP, \fB\-R\fP, \fB\-L\fP, \fB\-E\fP, \fB\-r\fP, \fB\-w\fP, \fB\-v\fP, a RPMC command or no operation.
If no operation is specified, \fBflashrom\fP will only probe for flash chips. It is recommended that if you try \fBflashrom\fP the
first time on a system, you run it in probe\-only mode and check the output.
Also you are advised to make a backup of your current ROM contents with \fB\-r\fP before you try to write a new image.
All operations involving any chip access (probe/read/write/...) require the \fB\-p/\-\-programmer\fP option to be used (please see below).
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
\fB\-r, \-\-read [<file>]\fP
Read flash ROM contents and save them into the given \fB<file>\fP\&.
If the file already exists, it will be overwritten.
.sp
The \fB<file>\fP parameter is required here unless reading is restricted to one or more flash regions via the \fB\-i/\-\-include\fP parameter
and the file is specified there. See the \fB\-\-include\fP section below for examples.
.TP
\fB\-w, \-\-write (<file>|\-)\fP
Write \fB<file>\fP into flash ROM. If \fB\-\fP is provided instead, contents will be read from stdin.
This will first automatically erase the chip, then write to it.
.sp
In the process the chip is also read several times. First an in\-memory backup is made for disaster recovery and to be
able to skip regions that are already equal to the image file.
This copy is updated along with the write operation. In case of erase errors it is even re\-read completely.
After writing has finished and if verification is enabled, the whole flash chip is read out and compared with the input image.
.sp
The \fB<file>\fP parameter is required here unless writing is restricted to one or more flash regions via the \fB\-i/\-\-include\fP parameter
and the file is specified there. See the \fB\-\-include\fP section below for examples.
.TP
\fB\-n, \-\-noverify\fP
Skip the automatic verification of flash ROM contents after writing or erasing. Using this option is \fBnot\fP recommended,
you should only use it if you know what you are doing and if you feel that the time for verification takes too long.
.sp
Typical usage is:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-n \-w <file>
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
This option is only useful in combination with \fB\-\-write\fP or \fB\-\-erase\fP\&.
.TP
\fB\-N, \-\-noverify\-all\fP
Skip not included regions during automatic verification after writing (cf. \fB\-l\fP and \fB\-i\fP).
You should only use this option if you are sure that communication with the flash chip is reliable
(e.g. when using the \fBinternal\fP programmer).
Even if \fBflashrom\fP is instructed not to touch parts of the flash chip, their contents could be damaged
(e.g. due to misunderstood erase commands).
.sp
This option is required to flash an Intel system with locked ME flash region using the \fBinternal\fP programmer.
It may be enabled by default in this case in the future.
.TP
\fB\-v, \-\-verify (<file>|\-)\fP
Verify the flash ROM contents against the given \fB<file>\fP\&.
If \fB\-\fP is provided instead, contents will be written to the stdout.
.sp
The \fB<file>\fP parameter is required here unless verification is restricted to one or more flash regions via the \fB\-i/\-\-include\fP parameter
and the file is specified there. See the \fB\-\-include\fP section below for examples.
.TP
\fB\-E, \-\-erase\fP
Erase the flash ROM chip.
.TP
\fB\-x, \-\-extract\fP
Extract every region defined on the layout from flash ROM chip to a file with the same name as the extracted region
(replacing spaces with underscores).
.TP
\fB\-V, \-\-verbose\fP
More verbose output. This option can be supplied multiple times (max. 3 times, i.e. \fB\-VVV\fP ) for even more debug output.
.TP
\fB\-c, \-\-chip <chipname>\fP
Probe only for the specified flash ROM chip. This option takes the chip name as printed by \fBflashrom \-L\fP without the
vendor name as parameter. Please note that the chip name is case sensitive.
.TP
\fB\-f, \-\-force\fP
Force one or more of the following actions:
.INDENT 7.0
.IP \(bu 2
Force chip read and pretend the chip is there.
.IP \(bu 2
Force chip access even if the chip is bigger than the maximum supported size for the flash bus.
.IP \(bu 2
Force erase even if erase is known bad.
.IP \(bu 2
Force write even if write is known bad.
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-l, \-\-layout <file>\fP
Read ROM layout from \fB<file>\fP\&.
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP supports ROM layouts. This allows you to flash certain parts of the flash chip only.
A ROM layout file contains multiple lines with the following syntax:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
startaddr:endaddr imagename
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBstartaddr\fP and \fBendaddr\fP are hexadecimal addresses within the ROM file and do not refer to any physical address.
Please note that using a 0x prefix for those hexadecimal numbers is not necessary, but you can\(aqt specify decimal/octal numbers.
\fBimagename\fP is an arbitrary name for the region/image from \fBstartaddr\fP to \fBendaddr\fP (both addresses included).
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
00000000:00008fff gfxrom
00009000:0003ffff normal
00040000:0007ffff fallback
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If you only want to update the image named \fBnormal\fP in a ROM based on the layout above, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-layout rom.layout \-\-image normal \-w some.rom
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
To update only the images named \fBnormal\fP and \fBfallback\fP, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-l rom.layout \-i normal \-i fallback \-w some.rom
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Overlapping sections are not supported.
.TP
\fB\-\-fmap\fP
Read layout from fmap in flash chip.
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP supports the fmap binary format which is commonly used by coreboot for partitioning a flash chip.
The on\-chip fmap will be read and used to generate the layout.
.sp
If you only want to update the \fBCOREBOOT\fP region defined in the fmap, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-fmap \-\-image COREBOOT \-w some.rom
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-fmap\-file <file>\fP
Read layout from a \fB<file>\fP containing binary fmap (e.g. coreboot roms).
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP supports the fmap binary format which is commonly used by coreboot for partitioning a flash chip.
The fmap in the specified file will be read and used to generate the layout.
.sp
If you only want to update the \fBCOREBOOT\fP region defined in the binary fmap file, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-fmap\-file some.rom \-\-image COREBOOT \-w some.rom
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-fmap\-verify\fP
Read ROM layout from fmap embedded in the ROM and verify that it matches the fmap in the file to be written.
.sp
This option is mutually exclusive with \fB\-\-fmap\fP, \fB\-\-fmap\-file\fP, \fB\-\-layout\fP, and \fB\-\-ifd\fP\&.
It can only be used with write operations, as it does not make sense otherwise. Before writing, \fBflashrom\fP
will read the fmap from both the flash chip and the file to be written, then compare them. If the fmaps do
not match, the write operation will be aborted.
.sp
This is useful to prevent accidentally writing a ROM image with an incompatible layout to a flash chip.
.sp
If you only want to update the \fBCOREBOOT\fP region defined in the fmap, and verify that the fmap matches, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-fmap\-verify \-w new.rom \-\-image COREBOOT
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-ifd\fP
Read ROM layout from Intel Firmware Descriptor.
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP supports ROM layouts given by an Intel Firmware Descriptor (IFD).
The on\-chip descriptor will be read and used to generate the layout. If you need to change the layout,
you have to update the IFD only first.
.sp
The following ROM images may be present in an IFD:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.nf
\fBfd\fP    \- the IFD itself
\fBbios\fP  \- the host firmware aka. BIOS
\fBme\fP    \- Intel Management Engine firmware
\fBgbe\fP   \- gigabit ethernet firmware
\fBpd\fP    \- platform specific data
.fi
.sp
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-i, \-\-include <region>[:<file>]\fP
Read, write, or verify only \fB<region>\fP to or from ROM.
The \fB\-i\fP option may be used multiple times if the user wishes to read, write, or verify multiple regions using a single command.
.sp
The user may optionally specify a corresponding \fB<file>\fP for any region they wish to read or write.
A read operation will read the corresponding regions from ROM and write individual files for each one.
A write option will read file(s) and write to the corresponding region(s) in ROM.
.sp
For all read/write/verify operations, the \fB<file>\fP parameter following those operations becomes optional and will be ignored
if present whenever the <file> is specified following the region.
.sp
Common rules for \-r/\-w/\-v syntax parsing:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
If no filename is specified at all, quit.
.IP \(bu 2
If a file is specified for \-r/\-w/\-v and no files are specified with
\-i args (or \-i is not used), then that file will be used for reading/
writing/verifying the entire ROM.
.IP \(bu 2
If no filename is specified for \-r/\-w/\-v, but files are specified
for \-i, then the number of file arguments for \-i options must be
equal to the total number of \-i options.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Rules for reading:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
If files are specified for \-i args but not \-r, do partial reads for
each \-i arg, creating a new file for each region. Each \-i option
must specify a filename.
.IP \(bu 2
If filenames are specified for \-r and \-i args, then:
.INDENT 2.0
.INDENT 3.5
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Do partial read for each \-i arg, creating a new file for
each region where a filename is provided (\-i region:filename).
.IP \(bu 2
Create a ROM\-sized file with partially filled content. For each
\-i arg, fill the corresponding offset with content from ROM.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Rules for writing and verifying:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
If files are specified for both \-w/\-v and \-i args, \-i files take
priority (files specified for \-w/\-v are unused).
.IP \(bu 2
If files are specified for \-i args but not \-w, do partial writes
for each \-i arg. Likewise for \-v and \-i args. All \-i args must
supply a filename. Any omission is considered ambiguous.
.IP \(bu 2
Regions with a filename associated must not overlap. This is also
considered ambiguous. Note: This is checked later since it requires
processing the layout/fmap first.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 7.0
.TP
.B Examples:
To read regions named \fBfoo\fP and \fBbar\fP in layout file \fB<layout>\fP into region\-sized files \fBfoo.bin\fP and \fBbar.bin\fP, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-r \-l <layout> \-i foo:foo.bin \-i bar:bar.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
To write files \fBfoo.bin\fP and \fBbar.bin\fP into regions named \fBfoo\fP and \fBbar\fP in layout file \fB<layout>\fP to the ROM, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-w \-l <layout> \-i foo:foo.bin \-i bar:bar.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
To verify regions named \fBfoo\fP and \fBbar\fP using layout file \fB<layout>\fP and files \fBfoo.bin\fP and \fBbar.bin\fP, run:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-v \-l <layout> \-i foo:foo.bin \-i bar:bar.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-status\fP
Prints the flash\(aqs current status register protection mode and write protection range.
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-list\fP
Prints a list of all protection ranges that the flash supports.
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-enable\fP
Enables hardware status register protection (SRP) if the flash supports it.
Once SRP is enabled, operations that change the flash\(aqs status registers (including \fB\-\-wp\-disable\fP and \fB\-\-wp\-range\fP)
can only be performed if the flash\(aqs #WP pin is at an inactive logic level.
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-disable\fP
Disables status register protection if the flash allows it.
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-range <start>,<length>\fP
Configures the flash to protect a range of addresses from <start> to (<start> + <length> \- 1), bounds inclusive.
The range must be supported by the flash, see \fB\-\-wp\-list\fP\&.
.TP
\fB\-\-wp\-region <region>\fP
Same as \fB\-\-wp\-range\fP but protects the range occupied by an image region.
This option requires a image layout to be specified, see \fB\-\-layout\fP\&.
The region must be supported by the flash, see \fB\-\-wp\-list\fP\&.
.TP
\fB\-\-flash\-name\fP
Prints out the detected flash chip\(aqs name.
.TP
\fB\-\-flash\-size\fP
Prints out the detected flash chip\(aqs size.
.TP
\fB\-\-flash\-contents <ref\-file>\fP
The file contents of \fB<ref\-file>\fP will be used to decide which parts of the flash need to be written.
Providing this saves an initial read of the full flash chip.
Be careful, if the provided data doesn\(aqt actually match the flash contents, results are undefined.
.TP
\fB\-L, \-\-list\-supported\fP
List the flash chips, chipsets, mainboards, and external programmers (including PCI, USB, parallel port, and serial port based devices)
supported by \fBflashrom\fP\&.
.sp
There are many unlisted boards which will work out of the box, without special support in \fBflashrom\fP\&.
Please let us know if you can verify that other boards work or do not work out of the box.
.sp
\fBIMPORTANT\fP:
For verification you have to test an ERASE and/or WRITE operation, so make sure you only do that if you have proper means to recover from failure!
.TP
\fB\-p, \-\-programmer <name>[:parameter[,parameter[,parameter]]]\fP
Specify the programmer device. This is mandatory for all operations involving any chip access (probe/read/write/...).
Currently supported are:
