.UNINDENT
.sp
Some programmers have optional or mandatory parameters which are described in detail in the
\fBPROGRAMMER\-SPECIFIC INFORMATION\fP section. Support for some programmers can be disabled at compile time.
\fBflashrom \-h\fP lists all supported programmers.
.TP
\fB\-h, \-\-help\fP
Show a help text and exit.
.TP
\fB\-o, \-\-output <logfile>\fP
Save the full debug log to \fB<logfile>\fP\&.
If the file already exists, it will be overwritten. This is the recommended way to gather logs from \fBflashrom\fP
because they will be verbose even if the on\-screen messages are not verbose and don\(aqt require output redirection.
.TP
\fB\-\-progress\fP
Show progress percentage of operations on the standard output.
.TP
\fB\-\-sacrifice\-ratio <ratio>\fP
Fraction (as a percentage, 0\-50) of an erase block that may be erased even if unmodified.
Larger values may complete programming faster, but may also hurt chip longevity by erasing cells unnecessarily.
.sp
Default is 0, S+1 size block only selected if all the S size blocks inside it need to be erased in full.
50 means that if more than a half of the area needs to be erased,
a S+1 size block can be selected to cover all the area with one erase.
The tradeoff is the speed of programming operation VS the longevity of the chip. Default is longevity.
.sp
DANGEROUS! It wears your chip faster!
.TP
\fB\-R, \-\-version\fP
Show version information and exit.
.UNINDENT
.SS RPMC commands
.sp
This section describes the commands added in JESD260. They are only supported on specific chip models.
If the chip is detected correctly but you still get \fBError: RPMC commands are not supported on this device\fP,
try using \fB\-c \(dqSFDP\-capable chip\(dq\fP for automatic feature detection.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
\fB\-\-get\-rpmc\-status\fP
Read the extended RPMC status by issuing a OP2 command
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-get\-rpmc\-status
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-write\-root\-key\fP
Write new root key from \fB\-\-rpmc\-root\-key\fP  file for \fB\-\-counter\-address\fP\&.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-write\-root\-key
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-update\-hmac\-key\fP
Update the hmac key register for \fB\-\-counter\-address\fP with the provided \fB\-\-key\-data\fP\&.
Requires valid \fB\-\-rpmc\-root\-key\fP\&.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-key\-data <value> \-\-update\-hmac\-key
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-increment\-counter <current>\fP
Increments the counter at \fB\-\-counter\-address\fP by one above the \fB<current>\fP\&.
Requires previously updated \fB\-\-key\-data\fP and valid \fB\-\-rpmc\-root\-key\fP\&.
.sp
Examples:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-key\-data <value> \-\-increment\-counter 12
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-key\-data <value> \-w rom.bin \-\-update\-hmac\-key \-\-increment\-counter 25
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-get\-counter\fP
Get the current counter value for \fB\-\-counter\-address\fP\&.
Requires previously updated \fB\-\-key\-data\fP and valid \fB\-\-rpmc\-root\-key\fP\&.
.sp
Examples:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-key\-data <value> \-\-get\-counter
flashrom \-p prog \-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile> \-\-counter\-address <address> \-\-key\-data <value> \-\-update\-hmac\-key \-\-get\-counter
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS RPMC options
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
\fB\-\-counter\-address <address>\fP
Target the counter at \fB<address>\fP for any RPMC operations.
Addressing starts at 0.
Defaults to 0.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-\-counter\-address 2
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-rpmc\-root\-key <keyfile>\fP
Use \fB<keyfile>\fP as location of 32\-byte root key.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-\-rpmc\-root\-key /home/user/some_key.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fB\-\-key\-data <value>\fP
Hexadecimal \fB<value>\fP will be used as 4\-byte key data in RPMC operations.
Defaults to 0.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-\-key\-data 12abc
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SH PROGRAMMER-SPECIFIC INFORMATION
.sp
Some programmer drivers accept further parameters to set programmer\-specific parameters. These parameters are separated
from the programmer name by a colon. While some programmers take arguments atfixed positions, other programmers use a
key/value interface in which the key and value is separated by an equal sign and different pairs are separated by a
comma or a colon.
.SS internal programmer
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
\fBBoard Enables\fP
Some mainboards require to run mainboard specific code to enable flash erase and write support
(and probe support on old systems with parallel flash).
The mainboard brand and model (if it requires specific code) is usually autodetected using one of the following mechanisms:
If your system is running coreboot, the mainboard type is determined from the coreboot table.
Otherwise, the mainboard is detected by examining the onboard PCI devices and possibly DMI info.
If PCI and DMI do not contain information to uniquely identify the mainboard (which is the exception),
or if you want to override the detected mainboard model, you can specify the mainboard using the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:mainboard=<vendor>:<board>
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax.
.sp
See the \fBKnown boards\fP or \fBKnown laptops\fP section in the output of \fBflashrom \-L\fP for a list of boards
which require the specification of the board name, if no coreboot table is found.
.sp
Some of these board\-specific flash enabling functions (called \fBboard enables\fP ) in \fBflashrom\fP have not yet been tested.
If your mainboard is detected needing an untested board enable function, a warning message is printed and the board enableis not executed,
because a wrong board enable function might cause the system to behave erratically, as board enable functions touch the
low\-level internals of a mainboard.
Not executing a board enable function (if one is needed) might cause detection or erasing failure.
If your board protects only part of the flash (commonly the top end, called boot block),
\fBflashrom\fP might encounter an error only after erasing the unprotected part, so running without the board\-enable function
might be dangerous for erase and write (which includes erase).
.sp
The suggested procedure for a mainboard with untested board specific code is to first try to probe the ROM
(just invoke \fBflashrom\fP and check that it detects your flash chip type) without running the board enable code
(i.e. without any parameters). If it finds your chip, fine. Otherwise, retry probing your chip with the board\-enable code running, using:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:boardenable=force
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If your chip is still not detected, the board enable code seems to be broken or the flash chip unsupported.
Otherwise, make a backup of your current ROM contents (using \fB\-r\fP) and store it to a medium outside of your computer,
like a USB drive or a network share. If you needed to run the board enable code already for probing, use it for reading too.
If reading succeeds and the contents of the read file look legit you can try to write the new image.
You should enable the board enable code in any case now, as it has been written because it is known that writing/erasing
without the board enable is going to fail. In any case (success or failure), please report to the \fBflashrom\fP mailing list, see below.
.TP
\fBCoreboot\fP
On systems running coreboot, \fBflashrom\fP checks whether the desired image matches your mainboard.
This needs some special board ID to be present in the image.
If \fBflashrom\fP detects that the image you want to write and the current board do not match,
it will refuse to write the image unless you specify:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:boardmismatch=force
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fBITE IT87 Super I/O\fP
If your mainboard is manufactured by GIGABYTE and supports DualBIOS it is very likely that it uses an
ITE IT87 series Super I/O to switch between the two flash chips.
Only one of them can be accessed at a time and you can manually select which one to use with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:dualbiosindex=chip
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBchip\fP is the index of the chip to use (0 = main, 1 = backup).
You can check which one is currently selected by leaving out the \fBchip\fP parameter.
.sp
If your mainboard uses an ITE IT87 series Super I/O for LPC<\->SPI flash bus translation, \fBflashrom\fP should autodetect that configuration.
If you want to set the I/O base port of the IT87 series SPI controller manually instead of using the value provided by the BIOS,
use the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:it87spiport=portnum
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBportnum\fP is the I/O port number (must be a multiple of 8).
In the unlikely case \fBflashrom\fP doesn\(aqt detect an active IT87 LPC<\->SPI bridge, please send a bug report so we can diagnose the problem.
.TP
\fBAMD chipsets\fP
Beginning with the SB700 chipset there is an integrated microcontroller (IMC) based on the 8051 embedded in every AMD southbridge.
Its firmware resides in the same flash chip as the host\(aqs which makes writing to the flash risky if the IMC is active.
Flashrom tries to temporarily disable the IMC but even then changing the contents of the flash can have unwanted effects:
when the IMC continues (at the latest after a reboot) it will continue executing code from the flash.
If the code was removed or changed in an unfortunate way it is unpredictable what the IMC will do.
Therefore, if \fBflashrom\fP detects an active IMC it will disable write support unless the user forces it with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:amd_imc_force=yes
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax. The user is responsible for supplying a suitable image or leaving out the IMC region with the help of a layout file.
This limitation might be removed in the future when we understand the details better and have received enough feedback from users.
Please report the outcome if you had to use this option to write a chip.
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus where applicable
(i.e.SB600 or later with an SPI flash chip directly attached to the chipset).
Syntax is:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP can be \fB\(aq16.5 MHz\(aq\fP, \fB\(aq22 MHz\(aq\fP, \fB\(aq33 MHz\(aq\fP, \fB\(aq66 MHz\(aq\fP, \fB\(aq100 MHZ\(aq\fP, or \fB\(aq800 kHz\(aq\fP\&.
Support of individual frequencies depends on the generation of the chipset:
.INDENT 7.0
.IP \(bu 2
SB6xx, SB7xx, SP5xxx: from 16.5 MHz up to and including 33 MHz.
The default is to use 16.5 MHz and disable Fast Reads.
.IP \(bu 2
SB8xx, SB9xx, Hudson: from 16.5 MHz up to and including 66 MHz.
The default is to use 16.5 MHz and disable Fast Reads.
.IP \(bu 2
Yangtze (with SPI 100 engine as found in Kabini and Tamesh): all of them.
The default is to use the frequency that is currently configured.
.UNINDENT
.sp
An optional \fBspireadmode\fP parameter specifies the read mode of the SPI bus where applicable (Bolton or later).
Syntax is:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:spireadmode=mode
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBmode\fP can be \fB\(aqNormal (up to 33 MHz)\(aq\fP, \fB\(aqNormal (up to 66 MHz)\(aq\fP, \fB\(aqDual IO (1\-1\-2)\(aq\fP, \fB\(aqQuad IO (1\-1\-4)\(aq\fP,
\fB\(aqDual IO (1\-2\-2)\(aq\fP, \fB\(aqQuad IO (1\-4\-4)\(aq\fP, or \fB\(aqFast Read\(aq\fP\&.
.sp
The default is to use the read mode that is currently configured.
.TP
\fBIntel chipsets\fP
If you have an Intel chipset with an ICH8 or later southbridge with SPI flash attached, and if a valid descriptor was written
to it (e.g. by the vendor), the chipset provides an alternative way to access the flash chip(s) named \fBHardware Sequencing\fP\&.
It is much simpler than the normal access method (called \fBSoftware Sequencing\fP), but does not allow the software to
choose the SPI commands to be sent. You can use the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:ich_spi_mode=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBvalue\fP can be \fBauto\fP, \fBswseq\fP or \fBhwseq\fP\&. By default (or when setting \fBich_spi_mode=auto\fP) the
module tries to use swseq and only activates hwseq if need be (e.g. if important opcodes are inaccessible due to lockdown;
or if more than one flash chip is attached). The other options (swseq, hwseq) select the respective mode (if possible).
.sp
ICH8 and later southbridges may also have locked address ranges of different kinds if a valid descriptor was written to it.
The flash address space is then partitioned in multiple so called \(dqFlash Regions\(dq containing the host firmware,
the ME firmware and so on respectively. The flash descriptor can also specify up to 5 so called \fBProtected Regions\fP,
which are freely chosen address ranges independent from the aforementioned \fBFlash Regions\fP\&.
All of them can be write and/or read protected individually.
.sp
If you have an Intel chipset with an ICH2 or later southbridge and if you want to set specific IDSEL values for a
non\-default flash chip or an embedded controller (EC), you can use the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:fwh_idsel=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBvalue\fP is the 48\-bit hexadecimal raw value to be written in the IDSEL registers of the Intel southbridge.
The upper 32 bits use one hex digit each per 512 kB range between 0xffc00000 and 0xffffffff, and the lower 16 bits
use one hex digit each per 1024 kB range between 0xff400000 and 0xff7fffff.
The rightmost hex digit corresponds with the lowest address range. All address ranges have a corresponding sister range
4 MB below with identical IDSEL settings. The default value for ICH7 is given in the example below.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:fwh_idsel=0x001122334567
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fBLaptops\fP
Using \fBflashrom\fP on older laptops that don\(aqt boot from the SPI bus is dangerous and may easily make your hardware unusable
(see also the \fBBUGS\fP section). The embedded controller (EC) in some machines may interact badly with flashing.
More information is at Info on laptops and EC \%<>\&.
Problems occur when the flash chip is shared between BIOS and EC firmware, and the latter does not expect \fBflashrom\fP
to access the chip. While \fBflashrom\fP tries to change the contents of that memory the EC might need to fetch new
instructions or data from it and could stop working correctly. Probing for and reading from the chip may also irritate
your EC and cause fan failure, backlight failure, sudden poweroff, and other nasty effects. \fBflashrom\fP will attempt to
detect if it is running on such a laptop and limit probing to SPI buses. If you want to probe the LPC bus anyway at your own risk, use:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:laptop=force_I_want_a_brick
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
We will not help you if you force flashing on a laptop because this is a really dumb idea.
.sp
You have been warned.
.sp
Currently we rely on the chassis type encoded in the DMI/SMBIOS data to detect laptops. Some vendors did not implement
those bits correctly or set them to generic and/or dummy values. \fBflashrom\fP will then issue a warning and restrict buses like above.
In this case you can use:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal:laptop=this_is_not_a_laptop
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
to tell \fBflashrom\fP (at your own risk) that it is not running on a laptop.
.UNINDENT
.SS dummy programmer
.sp
The dummy programmer operates on a buffer in memory only. It provides a safe and fast way to test various aspects of
\fBflashrom\fP and is mainly used in development and while debugging.
It is able to emulate some chips to a certain degree (basic identify/read/erase/write operations work).
.sp
An optional parameter specifies the bus types it should support. For that you have to use the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:bus=[type[+type[+type]]]
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBtype\fP can be \fBparallel\fP, \fBlpc\fP, \fBfwh\fP, \fBspi\fP in any order. If you specify bus without type,
all buses will be disabled. If you do not specify bus, all buses will be enabled.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:bus=lpc+fwh
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The dummy programmer supports flash chip emulation for automated self\-tests without hardware access.
If you want to emulate a flash chip, use the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=chip
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBchip\fP is one of the following chips (please specify only the chip name, not the vendor):
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
ST           \fBM25P10.RES\fP      SPI flash chip (128 kB, RES, page write)
.IP \(bu 2
SST          \fBSST25VF040.REMS\fP SPI flash chip (512 kB, REMS, byte write)
.IP \(bu 2
SST          \fBSST25VF032B\fP     SPI flash chip (4096 kB, RDID, AAI write)
.IP \(bu 2
Macronix     \fBMX25L6436\fP       SPI flash chip (8192 kB, RDID, SFDP)
.IP \(bu 2
Winbond      \fBW25Q128FV\fP       SPI flash chip (16384 kB, RDID)
.IP \(bu 2
Spansion     \fBS25FL128L\fP       SPI flash chip (16384 kB, RDID)
.IP \(bu 2
Dummy vendor \fBVARIABLE_SIZE\fP   SPI flash chip (configurable size, page write)
.UNINDENT
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=SST25VF040.REMS
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
To use \fBVARIABLE_SIZE\fP chip, \fBsize\fP must be specified to configure the size of the flash chip as a power of two.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=VARIABLE_SIZE,size=16777216,image=dummy.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
\fBPersistent images\fP
If you use flash chip emulation, flash image persistence is available as well by using the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=chip,image=image.rom
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBimage.rom\fP is the file where the simulated chip contents are read on \fBflashrom\fP startup and where the
chip contents on \fBflashrom\fP shutdown are written to.
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=M25P10.RES,image=dummy.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fBSPI write chunk size\fP
If you use SPI flash chip emulation for a chip which supports SPI page write with the default opcode,
you can set the maximum allowed write chunk size with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=chip,spi_write_256_chunksize=size
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBsize\fP is the number of bytes (min.& 1, max.& 256).
Example:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=M25P10.RES,spi_write_256_chunksize=5
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.TP
\fBSPI blacklist\fP
To simulate a programmer which refuses to send certain SPI commands to the flash chip, you can specify a blacklist of
SPI commands with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:spi_blacklist=commandlist
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBommandlist\fP is a list of two\-digit hexadecimal representations of SPI commands.
If commandlist is e.g. 0302, \fBflashrom\fP will behave as if the SPI controller refuses to run command 0x03 (READ) and command 0x02 (WRITE).
commandlist may be up to 512 characters (256 commands) long.
Implementation note: \fBflashrom\fP will detect an error during command execution.
.TP
\fBSPI ignorelist\fP
To simulate a flash chip which ignores (doesn\(aqt support) certain SPI commands, you can specify an ignorelist of SPI commands with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:spi_ignorelist=commandlist
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBcommandlist\fP is a list of two\-digit hexadecimal representations of SPI commands.
If commandlist is e.g. 0302, the emulated flash chip will ignore command 0x03 (READ) and command 0x02 (WRITE).
\fBcommandlist\fP may be up to 512 characters (256 commands) long.
Implementation note: \fBflashrom\fP won\(aqt detect an error during command execution.
.TP
\fBSPI status register\fP
You can specify the initial content of the chip\(aqs status register with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:spi_status=content\(dq
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBcontent\fP is a hexadecimal value of up to 24 bits. For example, \fB0x332211\fP assigns 0x11 to SR1,
0x22 to SR2 and 0x33 to SR3. Shorter value is padded to 24 bits with zeroes on the left.
See datasheet for chosen chip for details about the registers content.
.TP
\fBWrite protection\fP
Chips with emulated WP: \fBW25Q128FV\fP, \fBS25FL128L\fP\&.
.sp
You can simulate state of hardware protection pin (WP) with the:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:hwwp=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBstate\fP is \fByes\fP or \fBno\fP (default value). \fByes\fP means active state of the pin implies that chip is
write\-protected (on real hardware the pin is usually negated, but not here).
.TP
\fBFrequency\fP
Frequency can be specified in \fBHz\fP (default), \fBKHz\fP, or \fBMHz\fP (not case sensitive).
If \fBfreq\fP parameter is passed in from command line, commands will delay for certain time before returning,
so that to emulate the requested frequency.
.sp
Valid range is [1Hz, 8000Mhz] and there is no delay by default.
.sp
The delay of an SPI command is proportional to the number of bits send over SPI bus in both directions
and is calculated based on the assumption that we transfer at 1 bit/Hz:
.INDENT 7.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dummy:emulate=W25Q128FV,freq=64mhz
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS nic3com, nicrealtek, nicnatsemi, nicintel, nicintel_eeprom, nicintel_spi, gfxnvidia, ogp_spi, drkaiser, satasii, satamv, atahpt, atavia, atapromise, it8212 programmers
.sp
These programmers have an option to specify the PCI address of the card your want to use, which must be specified if
more than one card supported by the selected programmer is installed in your system. The syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p xxxx:pci=bb:dd.f
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBxxxx\fP is the name of the programmer, \fBbb\fP is the PCI bus number, \fBdd\fP is the PCI device number, and \fBb\fP
is the PCI function number of the desired device. Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p nic3com:pci=05:04.0
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Some of these programmers have more info below.
.SS atavia programmer
.sp
The VT6421A is a PATA/SATA PCI controller that can be found on various cheap PCI cards.
Currently there is a datasheet \%<http://\:spacehopper\:.org/\:mirrors/\:ftp\:.vtbridge\:.org/\:Docs/\:Storage/\:DS_VT6421A_100_CCPL\:.PDF>\&.
.sp
There exists a patch for flashrom that makes it possible to access the attached flash chip,
but it has problems with some cards. They seem to need an offset added to the chip address for unknown reasons.
.sp
Due to the mysterious address handling of the VIA VT6421A controller the user can specify an offset with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p atavia:offset=addr
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBaddr\fP will be interpreted as usual (leading 0x (0) for hexadecimal (octal) values, or else decimal).
.sp
