.sp
The revision consists of two characters that are printed below the \(dqVT6421A\(dq string on the chip
prefixed by 4 numbers that encode the production year and week.
The country is noted right of the revision.
.SS atapromise programmer
.sp
This programmer is currently limited to 32 kB, regardless of the actual size of the flash chip. This stems from the
fact that, on the tested device (a Promise Ultra100), not all of the chip\(aqs address lines were actually connected.
You may use this programmer to flash firmware updates, since these are only 16 kB in size (padding to 32 kB is required).
.SS nic3com programmer
.sp
flashrom supports some 3Com network cards to reflash the (parallel) flash attached to these cards,
but it is also possible to use these cards to reflash other chips which fit in there electrically.
Please note that the small number of address lines connected to the chip may make accessing large chips impossible.
The maximum supported chip size is 128KB.
.SS nicintel_spi programmer
.sp
Programmer for SPI flash ROMs on Intel Gigabit network cards. Tested on 32\-bit hardware/PCI only.
.SS nicintel_eeprom programmer
.sp
This is the first programmer module in \fBflashrom\fP that does not provide access to NOR flash chips but EEPROMs mounted on
gigabit Ethernet cards based on Intel\(aqs 82580 NIC. Because EEPROMs normally do not announce their size nor allow
themselves to be identified, the controller relies on correct size values written to predefined addresses within the chip.
\fBFlashrom\fP follows this scheme but assumes the minimum size of 16 kB (128 kb) if an unprogrammed EEPROM/card is detected.
Intel specifies following EEPROMs to be compatible:
Atmel AT25128, AT25256, Micron (ST) M95128, M95256 and OnSemi (Catalyst) CAT25CS128.
.SS gfxnvidia programmer
.sp
Flashrom supports some Nvidia graphic cards to reflash the (parallel) flash attached to these cards,
but it is also possible to use these cards to reflash other chips which fit in there electrically.
.SS satasii programmer
.sp
Flashrom supports some SiI ATA/SATA controllers to reflash the flash attached to these controller cards,
but it is also possible to use these cards to reflash other chips which fit in there electrically.
Please note that the small number of address lines connected to the chip may make accessing large chips impossible.
.SS ft2232_spi programmer
.sp
This module supports various programmers based on FTDI FT2232/FT4232H/FT232H chips including the DLP Design DLP\-USB1232H,
openbiosprog\-spi, Amontec JTAGkey/JTAGkey\-tiny/JTAGkey\-2, Dangerous Prototypes Bus Blaster, Olimex ARM\-USB\-TINY/\-H,
Olimex ARM\-USB\-OCD/\-H, OpenMoko Neo1973 Debug board (V2+), TIAO/DIYGADGET USB Multi\-Protocol Adapter (TUMPA), TUMPA Lite,
GOEPEL PicoTAP, Google Servo v1/v2, Tin Can Tools Flyswatter/Flyswatter 2 and Kristech KT\-LINK.
.sp
An optional parameter specifies the controller type, channel/interface/port it should support. For that you have to use the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \e\-p ft2232_spi:type=model,port=interface
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBmodel\fP can be \fB2232H\fP, \fB4232H\fP, \fB232H\fP, \fBjtagkey\fP, \fBbusblaster\fP, \fBopenmoko\fP, \fBarm\-usb\-tiny\fP,
\fBarm\-usb\-tiny\-h\fP, \fBarm\-usb\-ocd\fP, \fBarm\-usb\-ocd\-h\fP, \fBtumpa\fP, \fBtumpalite\fP, \fBpicotap\fP, \fBgoogle\-servo,
\(ga\(gagoogle\-servo\-v2\fP, \fBgoogle\-servo\-v2\-legacy\fP or \fBkt\-link\fP\&.
\fBinterface\fP can be \fBA\fP, \fBB\fP, \fBC\fP, or \fBD\fP\&. The default model is \fB4232H\fP, the default interface is \fBA\fP and
GPIO is not used by default.
.sp
If there is more than one ft2232_spi\-compatible device connected, you can select which one should be used by specifying
its serial number with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ft2232_spi:serial=number
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBnumber\fP is the serial number of the device (which can be found for example in the output of lsusb \-v).
.sp
All models supported by the \fBft2232_spi\fP driver can configure the SPI clock rate by setting a divisor. The expressible
divisors are all \fBeven\fP numbers between 2 and 2^17 (=131072) resulting in SPI clock frequencies of 6 MHz down to about
92 Hz for 12 MHz inputs (non\-H chips) and 30 MHz down to about 458 Hz for 60 MHz inputs (\(aqH\(aq chips). The default divisor
is set to 2, but you can use another one by specifying the optional \fBdivisor\fP parameter with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ft2232_spi:divisor=div
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax. Using the parameter \fBcsgpiol\fP (DEPRECATED \- use \fBgpiol\fP instead) an additional CS# pin can be chosen,
where the value can be a number between 0 and 3, denoting GPIOL0\-GPIOL3 correspondingly. Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ft2232_spi:csgpiol=3
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The parameter \fBgpiolX=[HLC]\fP allows use of the GPIOL pins either as generic gpios with a fixed value during flashing
or as additional CS# signal, where \fBX\fP can be a number between 0 and 3, denoting GPIOL0\-GPIOL3 correspondingly.
The parameter may be specified multiple times, one time per GPIOL pin. Valid values are \fBH\fP, \fBL\fP and \fBC\fP:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fBH\fP \- Set GPIOL output high
.IP \(bu 2
\fBL\fP \- Set GPIOL output low
.IP \(bu 2
\fBC\fP \- Use GPIOL as additional CS# output
.UNINDENT
.sp
Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ft2232_spi:gpiol0=H
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNote\fP that not all GPIOL pins are freely usable with all programmers as some have special functionality.
.SS serprog programmer
.sp
This module supports all programmers speaking the serprog protocol. This includes some Arduino\-based devices as well as
various programmers by Urja Rannikko, Juhana Helovuo, Stefan Tauner, Chi Zhang and many others.
.sp
A mandatory parameter specifies either a serial device (and baud rate) or an IP/port combination for communicating with
the programmer. The device/baud combination has to start with \fBdev=\fP and separate the optional baud rate with a colon.
For example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p serprog:dev=/dev/ttyS0:115200
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If no baud rate is given the default values by the operating system/hardware will be used.
For IP connections you have to use the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p serprog:ip=ipaddr:port
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax. In case the device supports it, you can set the SPI clock frequency with the optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter.
The frequency is parsed as hertz, unless an \fBM\fP, or \fBk\fP suffix is given, then megahertz or kilohertz are used respectively.
Example that sets the frequency to 2 MHz:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p serprog:dev=/dev/device:baud,spispeed=2M
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Optional \fBcs\fP parameter can be used to switch which chip select number is used. This allows connecting multiple
chips at once and selecting which one to flash by software means (rather than rewiring):
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p serprog:dev=/dev/device:baud,cs=0
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The particular programmer implementation needs to support this feature, for it to work. If the requested chip
select isn\(aqt available, flashrom will fail safely.
.sp
More information about serprog is available in this document: Serial Flasher Protocol Specification \%<>\&.
.SS buspirate_spi programmer
.sp
A required \fBdev\fP parameter specifies the Bus Pirate device node and an optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the
frequency of the SPI bus. The parameter delimiter is a comma. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:dev=/dev/device,spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP can be \fB30k\fP, \fB125k\fP, \fB250k\fP, \fB1M\fP, \fB2M\fP, \fB2.6M\fP, \fB4M\fP or \fB8M\fP (in Hz).
The default is the maximum frequency of 8 MHz.
.sp
The baud rate for communication between the host and the Bus Pirate can be specified with the optional \fBserialspeed\fP
parameter. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:serialspeed=baud
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBbaud\fP can be \fB115200\fP, \fB230400\fP, \fB250000\fP or \fB2000000\fP (\fB2M\fP).
The default is \fB2M\fP baud for Bus Pirate hardware version 3.0 and greater, and 115200 otherwise.
.sp
An optional pullups parameter specifies the use of the Bus Pirate internal pull\-up resistors. This may be needed if you
are working with a flash ROM chip that you have physically removed from the board. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:pullups=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBstate\fP can be \fBon\fP or \fBoff\fP\&.
More information about the Bus Pirate pull\-up resistors and their purpose is available
in a guide by dangerousprototypes \%<http://\:dangerousprototypes\:.com/\:docs/\:Practical_guide_to_Bus_Pirate_pull-up_resistors>\&.
.sp
When working with low\-voltage chips, the internal 10k pull\-ups of the Bus Pirate might be too high. In such cases, it\(aqs necessary to create an external pull\-up using lower\-value resistors.
.sp
For this, you can use the \fBhiz\fP parameter. This way, the Bus Pirate will operate as an open drain. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:hiz=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBstate\fP can be \fBon\fP or \fBoff\fP\&.
.sp
The state of the Bus Pirate power supply pins is controllable through an optional \fBpsus\fP parameter. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:psus=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBstate\fP can be \fBon\fP or \fBoff\fP\&.
This allows the bus pirate to power the ROM chip directly. This may also be used to provide the required pullup voltage
(when using the \fBpullups\fP option), by connecting the Bus Pirate\(aqs Vpu input to the appropriate Vcc pin.
.sp
An optional aux parameter specifies the state of the Bus Pirate auxiliary pin.
This may be used to drive the auxiliary pin high or low before a transfer.
Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p buspirate_spi:aux=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBstate\fP can be \fBhigh\fP or \fBlow\fP\&. The default \fBstate\fP is \fBhigh\fP\&.
.SS pickit2_spi programmer
.sp
An optional \fBvoltage\fP parameter specifies the voltage the PICkit2 should use. The default unit is Volt if no unit is specified.
You can use \fBmV\fP, \fBmillivolt\fP, \fBV\fP or \fBVolt\fP as unit specifier. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \e\-p pickit2_spi:voltage=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP can be \fB0V\fP, \fB1.8V\fP, \fB2.5V\fP, \fB3.5V\fP or the equivalent in mV.
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p pickit2_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP can be \fB250k\fP, \fB333k\fP, \fB500k\fP or \fB1M\fP (in Hz). The default is a frequency of 1 MHz.
.SS dediprog programmer
.sp
An optional \fBvoltage\fP parameter specifies the voltage the Dediprog should use. The default unit is Volt if no unit is specified.
You can use \fBmV\fP, \fBmilliVolt\fP, \fBV\fP or \fBVolt\fP as unit specifier. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dediprog:voltage=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP can be \fB0V\fP, \fB1.8V\fP, \fB2.5V\fP, \fB3.5V\fP or the equivalent in mV.
.sp
An optional \fBdevice\fP parameter specifies which of multiple connected Dediprog devices should be used.
Please be aware that the order depends on libusb\(aqs usb_get_busses() function and that the numbering starts at 0.
Usage example to select the second device:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dediprog:device=1
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus. The firmware on the device needs to be 5.0.0 or newer.
Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dediprog:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP can be \fB375k\fP, \fB750k\fP, \fB1.5M\fP, \fB2.18M\fP, \fB3M\fP, \fB8M\fP, \fB12M\fP or \fB24M\fP (in Hz).
The default is a frequency of 12 MHz.
.sp
An optional \fBtarget\fP parameter specifies which target chip should be used. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dediprog:target=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP can be \fB1\fP or \fB2\fP to select target chip 1 or 2 respectively. The default is target chip 1.
.SS rayer_spi programmer
.sp
The default I/O base address used for the parallel port is 0x378 and you can use the optional \fBiobase\fP parameter to
specify an alternate base I/O address with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p rayer_spi:iobase=baseaddr
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBbaseaddr\fP is base I/O port address of the parallel port, which must be a multiple of four.
Make sure to not forget the \(dq0x\(dq prefix for hexadecimal port addresses.
.sp
The default cable type is the RayeR cable. You can use the optional \fBtype\fP parameter to specify the cable type with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p rayer_spi:type=model
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBmodel\fP can be \fBrayer\fP for the RayeR cable, \fBbyteblastermv\fP for the Altera ByteBlasterMV,
\fBstk200\fP for the Atmel, \fBSTK200/300\fP, \fBwiggler\fP for the Macraigor Wiggler, \fBxilinx\fP for the Xilinx Parallel Cable III (DLC 5),
or \fBspi_tt\fP for SPI Tiny Tools\-compatible hardware.
.sp
More information about the RayeR hardware is available at RayeR\(aqs website \%<http://\:rayer\:.g6\:.cz/\:elektro/\:spipgm\:.htm>\&.
The Altera ByteBlasterMV datasheet can be obtained from Altera \%<http://\:www\:.altera\:.co\:.jp/\:literature/\:ds/\:dsbytemv\:.pdf>\&.
For more information about the Macraigor Wiggler see their company homepage \%<http://\:www\:.macraigor\:.com/\:wiggler\:.htm>\&.
The schematic of the Xilinx DLC 5 was published in a Xilinx guide \%<http://\:www\:.xilinx\:.com/\:support/\:documentation/\:user_guides/\:xtp029\:.pdf>\&.
.SS raiden_debug_spi programmer
.sp
Some devices such as the GSC knows how it is wired to AP and EC flash chips, and can be told which specific device to talk to using the \fBtarget\fP parameter:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p raiden_debug_spi:target={ap,ec}
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Other devices such as Servo Micro and HyperDebug are generic, and do not know how they are wired, the caller is responsible for first configure the appropriate MUXes or buffers, and then tell the debugger which port to use (Servo Micro has just one SPI port, HyperDebug is the first of this kind to have multiple):
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p raiden_debug_spi:target=N
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBN\fP is an non\-negative integer (default \fB0\fP).
.sp
The default is to use the first available servo. You can use the optional \fBserial\fP parameter to specify the servo
USB device serial number to use specifically with:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p raiden_debug_spi:serial=XXX
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The servo device serial number can be found via \fBlsusb\fP\&.
Raiden will poll the \fBap\fP target waiting for the system power to settle on the AP and EC flash devices.
.sp
The optional \fBcustom_rst=true\fP parameter alters the behavior of the reset process:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p raiden_debug_spi:custom_rst=<true|false>
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax, where:
.sp
\fBcustom_rst=false\fP is the implicit default timeout of 3ms
.sp
and \fBcustom_rst=true\fP set \fBRAIDEN_DEBUG_SPI_REQ_ENABLE_AP_CUSTOM\fP instead of \fBRAIDEN_DEBUG_SPI_REQ_ENABLE_AP\fP\&.
This custom reset will modify the timeout from 3ms to 10ms and will not set \fBEC_RST_L\fP, meaning neither the EC nor the AP will be reset. With this setting, it\(aqs the user\(aqs responsibility to manage the reset signal manually or by configuring the GPIO.
Failure to handle the reset signal appropriately will likely result in flashing errors.
.sp
More information about the ChromiumOS servo
hardware is available at servos website \%<https://\:chromium\:.googlesource\:.com/\:chromiumos/\:third_party/\:hdctools/\:+/\:HEAD/\:docs/\:servo_v4\:.md>\&.
.SS pony_spi programmer
.sp
The serial port (like /dev/ttyS0, /dev/ttyUSB0 on Linux or COM3 on windows) is specified using the mandatory \fBdev\fP
parameter. The adapter type is selectable between SI\-Prog (used for SPI devices with PonyProg 2000) or a custom made
serial bitbanging programmer named \(dqserbang\(dq. The optional \fBtype\fP parameter accepts the values \fBsi_prog\fP (default)
or \fBserbang\fP\&.
.sp
Information about the SI\-Prog adapter can be found at its website \%<http://\:www\:.lancos\:.com/\:siprogsch\:.html>\&.
.sp
An example call to \fBflashrom\fP is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p pony_spi:dev=/dev/ttyS0,type=serbang
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Please note that while USB\-to\-serial adapters work under certain circumstances, this slows down operation considerably.
.SS ogp_spi programmer
.sp
The flash ROM chip to access must be specified with the \fBrom\fP parameter:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ogp_spi:rom=name
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Where \fBname\fP is either \fBcprom\fP or \fBs3\fP for the configuration ROM and \fBbprom\fP or \fBbios\fP for the BIOS ROM.
If more than one card supported by the \fBogp_spi\fP programmer is installed in your system, you have to specify the PCI
address of the card you want to use with the \fBpci=\fP parameter as explained in the \fBnic3com\fP et al. section above.
.SS linux_mtd programmer
.sp
You may specify the MTD device to use with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p linux_mtd:dev=/dev/mtdX
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fB/dev/mtdX\fP is the Linux device node for your MTD device. If left unspecified the first MTD device found
(e.g. /dev/mtd0) will be used by default.
.sp
Please note that the linux_mtd driver only works on Linux.
.SS linux_spi programmer
.sp
You have to specify the SPI controller to use with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p linux_spi:dev=/dev/spidevX.Y
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fB/dev/spidevX.Y\fP is the Linux device node for your SPI controller.
.sp
In case the device supports it, you can set the SPI clock frequency with the optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter.
The frequency is parsed as kilohertz. Example that sets the frequency to 8 MHz:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p linux_spi:dev=/dev/spidevX.Y,spispeed=8000
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Please note that the linux_spi driver only works on Linux.
.SS mstarddc_spi programmer
.sp
The Display Data Channel (DDC) is an I2C bus present on VGA and DVI connectors, that allows exchanging information
between a computer and attached displays. Its most common uses are getting display capabilities through EDID
(at I2C address 0x50) and sending commands to the display using the DDC/CI protocol (at address 0x37).
On displays driven by MSTAR SoCs, it is also possible to access the SoC firmware flash (connected to the Soc through another SPI bus)
using an In\-System Programming (ISP) port, usually at address 0x49. This \fBflashrom\fP module allows the latter via Linux\(aqs I2C driver.
.sp
\fBIMPORTANT:\fP
Before using this programmer, the display \fBMUST\fP be in standby mode, and only connected to the computer that will run
\fBflashrom\fP using a VGA cable, to an inactive VGA output. It absolutely \fBMUST NOT\fP be used as a display during the procedure!
.sp
You have to specify the DDC/I2C controller and I2C address to use with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p mstarddc_spi:dev=/dev/i2c\-X:YY
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fB/dev/i2c\-X\fP is the Linux device node for your I2C controller connected to the display\(aqs DDC channel, and
\fBYY\fP is the (hexadecimal) address of the MSTAR ISP port (address 0x49 is usually used).
Example that uses I2C controller /dev/i2c\-1 and address 0x49:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p mstarddc_spi:dev=/dev/i2c\-1:49
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
It is also possible to inhibit the reset command that is normally sent to the display once the \fBflashrom\fP operation is
completed using the optional \fBnoreset\fP parameter. A value of 1 prevents \fBflashrom\fP from sending the reset command.
Example that does not reset the display at the end of the operation:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p mstarddc_spi:dev=/dev/i2c\-1:49,noreset=1
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Please note that sending the reset command is also inhibited if an error occurred during the operation.
To send the reset command afterwards, you can simply run \fBflashrom\fP once more, in chip probe mode (not specifying an operation),
without the \fBnoreset\fP parameter, once the flash read/write operation you intended to perform has completed successfully.
.sp
Please also note that the mstarddc_spi driver only works on Linux.
.SS ch341a_spi programmer
.sp
The WCH CH341A programmer does not support any parameters currently. SPI frequency is fixed at 2 MHz, and CS0 is used
as per the device.
.SS ch347_spi programmer
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter could be used to specify the SPI speed. This parameter is available for the CH347T and CH347F device.
The default SPI speed is 15MHz if no value is specified.
Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ch347_spi:spispeed=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP can be \fB60M\fP, \fB30M\fP, \fB15M\fP, \fB7.5M\fP, \fB3.75M\fP, \fB1.875M\fP, \fB937.5K\fP, \fB468.75K\fP\&.
.SS ni845x_spi programmer
.sp
An optional \fBvoltage\fP parameter could be used to specify the IO voltage. This parameter is available for the NI USB\-8452 device.
The default unit is Volt if no unit is specified. You can use \fBmV\fP, \fBmilliVolt\fP, \fBV\fP or \fBVolt\fP as unit specifier.
Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ni845x_spi:voltage=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP can be \fB1.2V\fP, \fB1.5V\fP, \fB1.8V\fP, \fB2.5V\fP, \fB3.3V\fP or the equivalent in mV.
.sp
In the case if none of the programmer\(aqs supported IO voltage is within the supported voltage range of the detected flash
chip the \fBflashrom\fP will abort the operation (to prevent damaging the flash chip).
You can override this behaviour by passing \fByes\fP to the \fBignore_io_voltage_limits\fP parameter
(for e.g. if you are using an external voltage translator circuit). Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ni845x_spi:ignore_io_voltage_limits=yes
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
You can use the \fBserial\fP parameter to explicitly specify which connected NI USB\-845x device should be used. You should
use your device\(aqs 7 digit hexadecimal serial number. Usage example to select the device with 1230A12 serial number:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ni845x_spi:serial=1230A12
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ni845x_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP should a number corresponding to the desired frequency in kHz.
The maximum \fBfrequency\fP is 12 MHz (12000 kHz) for the USB\-8451 and 50 MHz (50000 kHz) for the USB\-8452.
The default is a frequency of 1 MHz (1000 kHz).
.sp
An optional \fBcs\fP parameter specifies which target chip select line should be used. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p ni845x_spi:csnumber=value
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBvalue\fP should be between \fB0\fP and \fB7\fP\&. By default the CS0 is used.
.SS digilent_spi programmer
.sp
An optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p digilent_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBfrequency\fP can be \fB62.5k\fP, \fB125k\fP, \fB250k\fP, \fB500k\fP, \fB1M\fP, \fB2M\fP or \fB4M\fP (in Hz).
The default is a frequency of 4 MHz.
.SS dirtyjtag_spi programmer
.sp
An optional \fBfreq\fP parameter specifies the frequency of the SPI bus. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p dirtyjtag_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBspispeed\fP can be any value in hertz, kilohertz or megahertz supported by the programmer.
The default is a frequency of 100 KHz.
.SS jlink_spi programmer
.sp
This module supports SEGGER J\-Link and compatible devices.
.sp
The \fBMOSI\fP signal of the flash chip must be attached to \fBTDI\fP pin of the programmer, \fBMISO\fP to \fBTDO\fP and
\fBSCK\fP to \fBTCK\fP\&. The chip select (\fBCS\fP) signal of the flash chip can be attached to different pins of the
programmer which can be selected with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p jlink_spi:cs=pin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBpin\fP can be either \fBTRST\fP, \fBRESET\fP or \fBTMS\fP\&. The default pin for chip select is \fBRESET\fP\&.
Note that, when using \fBRESET\fP, it is normal that the indicator LED blinks orange or red.
.sp
Additionally, the \fBTref\fP pin of the programmer must be attached to the logic level of the flash chip.
The programmer measures the voltage on this pin and generates the reference
voltage for its input comparators and adapts its output voltages to it.
.sp
Pinout for devices with 20\-pin JTAG connector:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
  +\-\-\-\-\-\-\-+
  |  1  2 |     1: VTref     2:
  |  3  4 |     3: TRST      4: GND
  |  5  6 |     5: TDI       6: GND
+\-+  7  8 |     7: TMS       8: GND
|    9 10 |     9: TCK      10: GND
|   11 12 |    11:          12: GND
+\-+ 13 14 |    13: TDO      14:
  | 15 16 |    15: RESET    16:
  | 17 18 |    17:          18:
  | 19 20 |    19: PWR_5V   20:
  +\-\-\-\-\-\-\-+
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If there is more than one compatible device connected, you can select which one should be used by specifying its serial
number with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p jlink_spi:serial=number
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBnumber\fP is the serial number of the device (which can be found for example in the output of \fBlsusb \-v\fP).
.sp
The SPI speed can be selected by using the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p jlink_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBfrequency\fP is the SPI clock frequency in kHz. The maximum speed depends on the device in use.
.sp
The \fBpower=on\fP option can be used to activate the 5 V power supply (PWR_5V) of the J\-Link during a flash operation.
.SS stlinkv3_spi programmer
.sp
This module supports SPI flash programming through the STMicroelectronics STLINK V3 programmer/debugger\(aqs SPI bridge interface:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p stlinkv3_spi
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If there is more than one compatible device connected, you can select which one should be used by specifying its
serial number with the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p stlinkv3_spi:serial=number
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBnumber\fP is the serial number of the device (which can be found for example in the output of \fBlsusb \-v\fP).
.sp
The SPI speed can be selected by using the:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p stlinkv3_spi:spispeed=frequency
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
syntax where \fBfrequency\fP is the SPI clock frequency in kHz. If the passed frequency is not supported by the adapter
the nearest lower supported frequency will be used.
.SS realtek_mst_i2c_spi, parade_lspcon and mediatek_i2c_spi programmers
.sp
These programmers tunnel SPI commands through I2C\-connected devices. The I2C bus over which communication occurs must be
specified either by device path with the \fBdevpath\fP option:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p realtek_mst_i2c_spi:devpath=/dev/i2c\-8
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
or by a bus number with the \fBbus\fP option, which implies a device path like \fB/dev/i2c\-N\fP where \fBN\fP is the specified
bus number:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p parade_lspcon:bus=8
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS realtek_mst_i2c_spi programmer
.sp
This programmer supports SPI flash programming for chips attached to Realtek DisplayPort MST hubs, themselves accessed
through I2C (tunneling SPI flash commands through the MST hub\(aqs I2C connection with the host).
.SS In\-system programming (ISP) mode
.sp
The \fBreset_mcu\fP and \fBenter_isp\fP options provide control over device mode changes, where each can be set to \fB0\fP
or \fB1\fP to enable or disable the corresponding mode transition.
.sp
\fBenter_isp\fP defaults to \fB1\fP, and if enabled will issue commands to the MST hub when beginning operation to put it
into ISP mode.
.sp
\fBreset_mcu\fP defaults to \fB0\fP, and if enabled will issue a reset command to the MST hub on programming completion,
causing it to exit ISP mode and to reload its own firmware from flash.
.sp
\fBallow_brick\fP defaults to \fBno\fP, however must be set explicitly to \fByes\fP to allow the driver to run if you are sure
you have a MST chip.
.sp
The hub must be in ISP mode for SPI flash access to be possible, so it is usually only useful to disable \fBenter_isp\fP
if an earlier invocation avoided resetting it on completion. For instance, to erase the flash and rewrite it with the
contents of a file without resetting in between (which could render it nonfunctional if attempting to load firmware
from a blank flash):
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p realtek_mst_i2c_spi:bus=0,enter_isp=1,reset_mcu=0 \-E

flashrom \-p realtek_mst_i2c_spi:bus=0,enter_isp=0,reset_mcu=1 \-w new.bin
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS parade_lspcon programmer
.sp
This programmer supports SPI flash programming for chips attached to Parade Technologies DisplayPort\-to\-HDMI level
shifter/protocol converters (LSPCONs), e.g. the PS175. Communication to the SPI flash is tunneled through the LSPCON
over I2C.
.SS mediatek_i2c_spi programmer
.sp
This programmer supports SPI flash programming for chips attached to some Mediatek display controllers, themselves
accessed through I2C (tunneling SPI flash commands through an I2C connection with the host).
.sp
The programmer is designed to support the TSUMOP82JUQ integrated display driver and scaler as used in the Google Meet
Series One Desk 27 (which runs a version of ChromeOS and uses \fBflashrom\fP in its \fBtsum\-scaler\-updater\fP scripts that ship
with the OS). Other chips may use compatible protocols but have not been tested with this programmer, and external chip
IOs may need to be controlled through other non\- \fBflashrom\fP means to configure the chip in order for it to operate as expected.
.sp
\fBdevpath\fP and \fBbus\fP options select the I2C bus to use, as described previously. \fBallow_brick\fP defaults to \fBno\fP,
and must explicitly be set to \fByes\fP in order for the programmer to operate. This is required because there is no
mechanism in the driver to positively identify that a given I2C bus is actually connected to a supported device.
.SS spidriver programmer
.sp
This is a SPI hardware interface with a display (\%<https://\:spidriver\:.com/>),
connected as an FT230X USB serial device at a fixed baud rate of 460800.
.sp
Firmware: \%<https://\:github\:.com/\:jamesbowman/\:spidriver>
.sp
A required \fBdev\fP parameter specifies the Excamera Labs SPIDriver device node
and an optional \fBmode\fP parameter specifies the mode of the SPI bus. The
parameter delimiter is a comma. Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p spidriver:dev=/dev/device,mode=0
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBmode\fP can be \fB0\fP, \fB1\fP, \fB2\fP or \fB3\fP\&. The default is mode 0.
Setting the SPI mode requires version 2 of the device firmware.
.sp
An optional A and/or B parameter specifies the state of the SPIDriver A and B pins.
This may be used to drive the A or B pins high or low before a transfer.
Syntax is:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p spidriver:a=state,b=state
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
where \fBstate\fP can be \fBhigh\fP or \fBlow\fP\&. The default \fBstate\fP is \fBhigh\fP\&.
.SS nv_sma_spi programmer
.sp
System Management Agent (SMA) programmer is a SoC which is working as a side band management on Nvidia server board.
One of its functions is to flash firmware to other components.
.sp
The Optional \fBcs\fP parameter can be used to switch which chip select number is used. This allows connecting multiple
chips at once and selecting which one to flash.:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p nv_sma_spi:cs=0
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The optional \fBbus\fP and \fBdevnum\fP parameters indicate which Nvidia System Management Agent is selected when multiple
SMAs are present. Both parameters must be specified simultaneously.:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p nv_sma_spi:bus=0,devnum=1
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The optional \fBspispeed\fP parameter sets the target frequency in Hz. The Nvidia System Management Agent selects the closest
supported frequency based on its capabilities. If the spispeed is not provided, the device default frequncy is used. An example
to set target frequency at 15MHz.:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p nv_sma_spi:spispeed=15000000
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SH EXAMPLES
.sp
To back up and update your BIOS, run:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal \-r backup.rom \-o backuplog.txt
flashrom \-p internal \-w newbios.rom \-o writelog.txt
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Please make sure to copy backup.rom to some external media before you try to write. That makes offline recovery easier.
.sp
If writing fails and \fBflashrom\fP complains about the chip being in an unknown state, you can try to restore the backup by running:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
flashrom \-p internal \-w backup.rom \-o restorelog.txt
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If you encounter any problems, please contact us and supply backuplog.txt, writelog.txt and restorelog.txt.
See section \fBBUGS\fP for contact info.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.sp
\fBflashrom\fP exits with 0 on success, 1 on most failures but with 3 if a call to mmap() fails.
