.SH LAPTOPS
.sp
Using \fBflashrom\fP on older laptops is dangerous and may easily make your hardware unusable. \fBflashrom\fP will attempt to detect
if it is running on a susceptible laptop and restrict flash\-chip probing for safety reasons. Please see the detailed
discussion of this topic and associated \fBflashrom\fP options in the \fBLaptops\fP paragraph in the \fBinternal programmer\fP
subsection of the \fBPROGRAMMER\-SPECIFIC INFORMATION\fP section and the information at Info on laptops and EC \%<>\&.
.sp
One\-time programmable (OTP) memory and unique IDs
.sp
Some flash chips contain OTP memory often denoted as \fBsecurity registers\fP\&. They usually have a capacity in the range
of some bytes to a few hundred bytes and can be used to give devices unique IDs etc. \fBflashrom\fP is not able to read
or write these memories and may therefore not be able to duplicate a chip completely. For chip types known to include
OTP memories a warning is printed when they are detected.
.sp
Similar to OTP memories are unique, factory programmed, unforgeable IDs. They are not modifiable by the user at all.
